1
00:01:24,017 --> 00:01:28,954
<i>[Humming]</i>

2
00:02:42,795 --> 00:02:45,423
<i>[Man] Yes, ma'am, how ya doin'?</i>

3
00:02:45,498 --> 00:02:47,796
<i>Is this Rose Hill?</i>

4
00:02:47,867 --> 00:02:50,427
<i>Good.
This is Ed Couch.</i>

5
00:02:50,503 --> 00:02:52,937
<i>I'm Vesta Adcock's nephew.</i>

6
00:02:53,006 --> 00:02:55,236
<i>I need to get up there
and see her,</i>

7
00:02:55,308 --> 00:02:59,301
<i>but I'm gonna be late
'cause I'm lost out here.</i>

8
00:02:59,379 --> 00:03:01,847
<i>We're off the Alabama interstate
but I don't know where.</i>

9
00:03:01,915 --> 00:03:05,407
<i>[Train Whistle]</i>

10
00:03:07,320 --> 00:03:11,654
<i>[Train Chugging]</i>

11
00:03:22,869 --> 00:03:25,429
<i>[Train Rumbling]</i>

12
00:03:38,284 --> 00:03:42,186
Did you hear that?
What?

13
00:03:42,255 --> 00:03:44,314
The train.

14
00:03:44,390 --> 00:03:47,257
No, I didn't hear
no train.

15
00:03:49,028 --> 00:03:51,360
Oh, nothin',
I guess.

16
00:03:51,431 --> 00:03:55,834
Where's "Whistle Stop" on
the map? I can't find it.

17
00:03:55,902 --> 00:03:59,770
Why did you tell me to
turn right 10 miles back there?

18
00:04:01,307 --> 00:04:04,834
God, you got a negative
sense of direction, hon.

19
00:04:04,911 --> 00:04:07,778
[Woman]
I'm sorry.

20
00:04:07,847 --> 00:04:12,045
Oh, Ed, your aunt's gonna be
so disappointed we're late.

21
00:04:12,118 --> 00:04:16,111
I know she's been looking forward
to this visit all week long.

22
00:04:16,189 --> 00:04:19,454
Bless her sweet,
little ol' heart.

23
00:04:23,596 --> 00:04:26,463
Hey, how's my sweet Auntie V
this afternoon?

24
00:04:26,532 --> 00:04:29,126
Remember us?

25
00:04:29,202 --> 00:04:32,262
<i>Don't you look pretty!
We brought you something.</i>

26
00:04:32,338 --> 00:04:35,501
<i>[Ed] Let me look at
you. [Auntie V: Grunting]</i>

27
00:04:35,575 --> 00:04:38,169
<i>[Ed] Don't you know Evelyn loves you?</i>

28
00:04:38,244 --> 00:04:43,079
Well, honey, I guess it'd be
better if you wait out here for me.

29
00:04:43,149 --> 00:04:47,609
I'll get all this stuff.
Well, if you think it's best.

30
00:04:47,687 --> 00:04:50,986
Yeah, I do this time.
Okay?

31
00:04:51,057 --> 00:04:53,218
Have a nice day,
Aunt Vesta.

32
00:04:53,293 --> 00:04:55,227
<i>[Ed] Don't you pitch a fit like that!</i>

33
00:05:07,206 --> 00:05:09,902
Did you know
they took my gallbladder out?

34
00:05:11,344 --> 00:05:13,471
No, I didn't.

35
00:05:13,546 --> 00:05:17,209
<i>Oh, yes. Still
in the hospital in a jar.</i>

36
00:05:17,283 --> 00:05:22,084
I guess that's where
they keep 'em.

37
00:05:22,155 --> 00:05:24,123
I guess.

38
00:05:24,190 --> 00:05:26,420
When I was
in the hospital,

39
00:05:26,492 --> 00:05:30,451
the nurse gave me one of them
Fleet enemas they're so fond of.

40
00:05:30,530 --> 00:05:33,124
Mrs. Cleo Threadgoode,

41
00:05:33,199 --> 00:05:36,498
82 year old widow,
imagine that.

42
00:05:36,569 --> 00:05:39,697
Actually,
everybody calls me Ninny.

43
00:05:39,772 --> 00:05:42,002
'Course I'm
just visitin' here.

44
00:05:42,075 --> 00:05:47,342
Did you ever have
one of them Fleet enemas?

45
00:05:47,413 --> 00:05:49,347
Um, well?

46
00:05:49,415 --> 00:05:51,474
No.

47
00:05:51,551 --> 00:05:54,782
You'd remember it.

48
00:05:54,854 --> 00:05:58,517
Me and my friend, Mrs. Otis,
come from Whistle Stop.

49
00:05:58,591 --> 00:06:00,786
You ever been
to Whistle Stop?

50
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:04,261
Why, yes. I just
passed by there today.

51
00:06:04,330 --> 00:06:09,199
<i>She's lived down the street
from me for 30 years or more.</i>

52
00:06:09,268 --> 00:06:11,259
After her son died,

53
00:06:11,337 --> 00:06:14,932
her daughter-in-law had a fit for
her to come live at the nursing home.

54
00:06:15,007 --> 00:06:18,306
They asked me to come
and be her roommate.

55
00:06:18,378 --> 00:06:22,610
<i>Mrs. Otis don't know it, but I'm going
home just soon as she gets settled in good.</i>

56
00:06:24,951 --> 00:06:28,352
Does the name "Idgie
Threadgoode" ring a bell?

57
00:06:28,421 --> 00:06:31,948
Um, no, ma'am.
I don't think so.

58
00:06:32,024 --> 00:06:34,822
You'd remember her.

59
00:06:34,894 --> 00:06:38,796
You see, I was practically
adopted by the Threadgoode family.

60
00:06:38,865 --> 00:06:41,197
I married her brother,
Cleo. Oh, uh-huh.

61
00:06:41,267 --> 00:06:46,034
<i>Idgie and her friend, Ruth,
ran the Whistle Stop Cafe.</i>

62
00:06:46,105 --> 00:06:48,039
<i>Oh.</i>

63
00:06:48,107 --> 00:06:50,803
Idgie was a character,
all right.

64
00:06:50,877 --> 00:06:54,210
<i>But how anybody
could've thought...</i>

65
00:06:54,280 --> 00:06:58,307
<i>she murdered that man
is beyond me.</i>

66
00:06:58,384 --> 00:07:00,352
I beg your pardon?

67
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:03,981
You sit and relax a while.
I'll tell you all about it.

68
00:07:04,056 --> 00:07:06,684
Oh, now, let's see.

69
00:07:06,759 --> 00:07:10,217
I 'member the day they pulled
that truck up out of the river.

70
00:07:10,296 --> 00:07:14,255
<i>[Ninny] That same rainy, summer day...</i>

71
00:07:14,333 --> 00:07:19,270
<i>Idgie Threadgoode was arrested for
the murder of the owner of that truck,</i>

72
00:07:19,338 --> 00:07:22,307
<i>Frank Bennett.</i>

73
00:07:24,610 --> 00:07:27,044
I guess,
to understand Idgie,

74
00:07:27,113 --> 00:07:30,810
you'd have to start way back
with her brother, Buddy.

75
00:07:30,883 --> 00:07:35,820
<i>Idgie was Buddy's pet
from the day she was born.</i>

76
00:07:38,224 --> 00:07:41,990
<i>I 'member the day we was all
gettin'ready for Leona's weddin'.</i>

77
00:07:42,061 --> 00:07:44,029
<i>The war had just ended,</i>

78
00:07:44,096 --> 00:07:46,428
<i>the Great one,
you know.</i>

79
00:07:46,499 --> 00:07:51,163
<i>And another one was about to
begin in the Threadgoode house.</i>

80
00:07:51,237 --> 00:07:53,671
<i>[Woman] Sipsey, honey, is that finished?</i>

81
00:07:55,241 --> 00:07:58,176
<i>Buddy, get dressed, honey. Mama?</i>

82
00:07:58,244 --> 00:08:00,212
Leona, what is it?

83
00:08:00,279 --> 00:08:02,144
Idgie's upstairs
in her room...

84
00:08:02,215 --> 00:08:04,183
and says she won't come out
as long as she lives.

85
00:08:04,250 --> 00:08:06,377
She is gonna ruin my weddin'! Shh.

86
00:08:06,452 --> 00:08:09,250
Leona, you're gonna be
the most beautiful bride.

87
00:08:09,322 --> 00:08:12,587
Of course she is, Papa.

88
00:08:12,658 --> 00:08:16,594
Your papa has spent every last
nickel he has just to make you happy.

89
00:08:16,662 --> 00:08:20,462
Now, you try to act
a little grateful, young lady.

90
00:08:20,533 --> 00:08:23,627
Imogene Louise Threadgoode!

91
00:08:23,703 --> 00:08:26,228
This is your mama!

92
00:08:28,641 --> 00:08:33,578
You come down here right now.
Do you hear me?

93
00:08:33,646 --> 00:08:36,274
Buddy, fetch her. She'll listen
to you. Come on down, little bit.

94
00:08:36,349 --> 00:08:38,909
<i>[Buddy] There's no firin'
squad waitin' for you.</i>

95
00:08:38,985 --> 00:08:44,321
<i>[Mama] Ohh! Come on,
honey. Let us see you.</i>

96
00:08:44,390 --> 00:08:46,551
<i>You look so pretty.</i>

97
00:08:46,626 --> 00:08:49,459
<i>I see London, I see... Hush!</i>

98
00:08:51,197 --> 00:08:54,633
Julian, hush.

99
00:08:54,700 --> 00:08:57,430
<i>Come ahead, sweetheart.</i>

100
00:08:57,503 --> 00:09:01,234
<i>[Mama] You look awful nice in that.</i>

101
00:09:01,307 --> 00:09:02,899
Mama!
You look fine.

102
00:09:02,975 --> 00:09:05,466
<i>[Julian]
She looks like a monkey.</i>

103
00:09:05,545 --> 00:09:07,342
<i>Julian, stop it
right this second!</i>

104
00:09:07,413 --> 00:09:10,746
<i>[Idgie] Take it back!
Take it back! Idgie, hey!</i>

105
00:09:10,816 --> 00:09:13,910
I told you she
was gonna ruin my weddin'!

106
00:09:13,986 --> 00:09:16,352
<i>Idgie, get up.
Take it back!</i>

107
00:09:16,422 --> 00:09:18,583
Take it back!

108
00:09:18,658 --> 00:09:21,991
I'll get you for this.
No, Buddy.

109
00:09:22,662 --> 00:09:25,722
<i>[Leona:
Sobbing]</i>

110
00:09:25,798 --> 00:09:28,858
<i>[Mama] We have to be careful
when she's dressing up.</i>

111
00:09:28,935 --> 00:09:30,869
<i>[Leona]
She's just a pain!</i>

112
00:09:30,937 --> 00:09:34,464
<i>Leona, will you
stop shrieking!</i>

113
00:09:34,540 --> 00:09:37,236
<i>This is your
weddin'day!</i>

114
00:09:48,254 --> 00:09:51,087
<i>[Buddy] Looks like you got
yourself up a tree, little bit.</i>

115
00:09:51,157 --> 00:09:54,183
[Idgie] I'm sick of
people makin' fun of me.

116
00:09:54,260 --> 00:09:56,785
So you're gonna stay up here
all day long.

117
00:09:56,862 --> 00:10:00,059
Yep.
The hell with them.

118
00:10:00,132 --> 00:10:04,068
Who wants to wear
that stupid ol' dress anyway?

119
00:10:04,136 --> 00:10:07,503
<i>I ever tell you about
the oysters? Oysters?</i>

120
00:10:07,573 --> 00:10:09,507
I tell you about the oysters? No.

121
00:10:09,575 --> 00:10:14,239
<i>[Buddy] Think about the millions
of oysters lyin'around the ocean.</i>

122
00:10:14,313 --> 00:10:16,645
Then one day...

123
00:10:16,716 --> 00:10:19,514
God comes along and sees one
and he says,

124
00:10:19,585 --> 00:10:22,486
"I think I'm gonna make
that one different."

125
00:10:22,555 --> 00:10:24,750
You know what he does?

126
00:10:24,824 --> 00:10:27,987
He puts a little
piece of sand in it.

127
00:10:28,060 --> 00:10:32,292
Guess what it can do that
the others can't. What?

128
00:10:32,365 --> 00:10:35,664
It can make
a beautiful pearl.

129
00:10:35,735 --> 00:10:37,896
What if God
made a mistake?

130
00:10:37,970 --> 00:10:43,067
Well, the way I figure it,
he never makes mistakes.

131
00:10:43,142 --> 00:10:45,906
I mean, he made sure
we got together.

132
00:10:45,978 --> 00:10:47,969
He made sure you got
the best looking,

133
00:10:48,047 --> 00:10:50,242
most charmin' brother
in the world...

134
00:10:50,316 --> 00:10:53,683
who's gonna beat you to the
chocolate cake. You will not.

135
00:10:53,753 --> 00:10:56,119
Got you out of the tree,
didn't I?

136
00:10:56,188 --> 00:10:59,123
Did not!

137
00:10:59,191 --> 00:11:02,820
<i>[Reverend] Into this estate,
these two come now to be joined.</i>

138
00:11:02,895 --> 00:11:04,988
<i>If any man present
can show cause...</i>

139
00:11:05,064 --> 00:11:07,464
<i>why they may not lawfully
be joined together,</i>

140
00:11:07,533 --> 00:11:12,664
let him speak now or
forever after hold his peace.

141
00:11:12,738 --> 00:11:15,400
Please be seated.

142
00:11:17,777 --> 00:11:19,972
If either of you
know any reason...

143
00:11:20,046 --> 00:11:23,015
<i>why you may not justly be joined
together in holy matrimony,</i>

144
00:11:23,082 --> 00:11:25,550
do you now confess it?

145
00:11:35,194 --> 00:11:37,890
It is then your will
to proceed.

146
00:11:37,963 --> 00:11:41,660
<i>Do you,
Charles Osgood Justice...</i>

147
00:11:47,506 --> 00:11:50,839
<i>[Mama] Thank you. I don't know what
we'd do without your generosity.</i>

148
00:11:50,910 --> 00:11:53,879
Sipsey, especially you.
Look what you've done!

149
00:11:53,946 --> 00:11:57,882
[Sipsey] Thank you, Mrs.
Threadgoode. Gimme that, you rascal!

150
00:12:02,221 --> 00:12:04,781
Ohh!
Jump on my back.

151
00:12:04,857 --> 00:12:08,486
<i>[Ninny] I don't think there ever was
a sweeter boy than Buddy Threadgoode.</i>

152
00:12:08,561 --> 00:12:13,055
You look beautiful, Lily.
Yes, Lily, you sure do.

153
00:12:13,132 --> 00:12:16,568
<i>[Ninny] I had the biggest crush on him.</i>

154
00:12:16,635 --> 00:12:18,967
<i>He was a terrible flirt!</i>

155
00:12:19,038 --> 00:12:22,269
<i>But his heart belonged
to Ruth Jamison.</i>

156
00:12:22,341 --> 00:12:25,504
<i>She was the daughter of
a friend of his mama's...</i>

157
00:12:25,578 --> 00:12:28,376
<i>who was visitin'
that summer.</i>

158
00:12:28,447 --> 00:12:31,905
Ruth Jamison, you're just
the one I've been lookin' for.

159
00:12:31,984 --> 00:12:35,078
Are you thirsty? Let's
go visit someplace else.

160
00:12:35,154 --> 00:12:38,089
<i>["My Blue Heaven"]</i>

161
00:12:38,157 --> 00:12:40,921
<i>A little nest
that's nestled</i>

162
00:12:40,993 --> 00:12:44,326
Think that's a big lake, you should've
seen the one next to our house.

163
00:12:44,396 --> 00:12:46,523
We used to swim in it
and fish.

164
00:12:46,599 --> 00:12:49,261
I sure do miss it.
Sure do.

165
00:12:49,335 --> 00:12:52,065
What happened to it?
Did it dry up?

166
00:12:52,138 --> 00:12:54,072
No, worse than that.

167
00:12:54,140 --> 00:12:56,199
Last fall,
a flock of ducks,

168
00:12:56,275 --> 00:13:00,541
<i>40 or 50 of'em, landed right
smack in the middle of it.</i>

169
00:13:00,613 --> 00:13:02,478
This fluke thing
happened.

170
00:13:02,548 --> 00:13:05,016
The temperature dropped so fast
that the whole lake froze...

171
00:13:05,084 --> 00:13:07,075
in three seconds,
just like that!

172
00:13:07,153 --> 00:13:09,451
Those poor little ducks.
Did it kill them?

173
00:13:09,522 --> 00:13:12,719
No, they flew off
and took the lake with 'em.

174
00:13:12,792 --> 00:13:16,159
To this very day, that lake
is somewhere over in Georgia.

175
00:13:16,228 --> 00:13:19,664
Buddy Threadgoode.

176
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:33,976
[Giggling] Come a little closer.
I wanna give you something.

177
00:13:34,046 --> 00:13:36,480
<i>[Buddy]
Come here.</i>

178
00:13:40,352 --> 00:13:42,582
Whoop!

179
00:13:42,655 --> 00:13:46,648
<i>You'll see
a smiling face</i>

180
00:13:46,725 --> 00:13:50,126
<i>[Buddy] Come back here, hat.
Where do you think you're goin'?</i>

181
00:13:52,364 --> 00:13:54,298
Whoa!

182
00:13:54,366 --> 00:13:57,460
I got it. Hold on, Ruth.
Hold on, little bit.

183
00:14:01,874 --> 00:14:04,604
It's all right.
I got it.

184
00:14:06,745 --> 00:14:10,476
Come here, you damn hat. Got it!

185
00:14:10,549 --> 00:14:13,484
<i>[Buddy] Oh, I meant to do that.</i>

186
00:14:14,553 --> 00:14:18,284
I... got it!

187
00:14:18,357 --> 00:14:20,222
<i>Ta-da!</i>

188
00:14:22,027 --> 00:14:24,552
All right.
Damn!

189
00:14:24,630 --> 00:14:26,598
Come on.

190
00:14:29,635 --> 00:14:33,162
<i>[Train Whistle]</i>

191
00:14:33,239 --> 00:14:38,108
Come on. Get out.
Get out.

192
00:14:38,177 --> 00:14:40,111
Buddy!

193
00:14:40,179 --> 00:14:43,410
<i>- Buddy!
- Buddy Threadgoode!</i>

194
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:46,745
<i>[Idgie]
Come on, Buddy!</i>

195
00:14:46,819 --> 00:14:48,548
Get out.

196
00:14:50,022 --> 00:14:52,149
Get out of there.

197
00:14:53,492 --> 00:14:57,292
<i>[Idgie]
Buddy!</i>

198
00:14:57,363 --> 00:15:00,491
<i>- Come on, Buddy!
- Buddy!</i>

199
00:15:00,566 --> 00:15:03,160
Buddy!

200
00:15:05,704 --> 00:15:08,298
No-o-o!

201
00:15:08,374 --> 00:15:12,208
<i>[Idgie]
Buddy!</i>

202
00:15:12,278 --> 00:15:15,679
<i>Buddy, no!
No!</i>

203
00:15:15,748 --> 00:15:18,512
<i>No! Buddy!
No-o-o!</i>

204
00:15:18,584 --> 00:15:21,610
No! Buddy!
Let me go!

205
00:15:23,088 --> 00:15:26,888
- No!
- Buddy!

206
00:15:26,959 --> 00:15:30,588
<i>[Man] You got to go back
to the house. [Screaming]</i>

207
00:15:30,663 --> 00:15:33,154
<i>Come on.
We're gonna go home.</i>

208
00:15:33,232 --> 00:15:36,065
- Buddy!
- You have to be strong.

209
00:15:36,135 --> 00:15:39,036
It'll be okay.
Buddy!

210
00:15:39,104 --> 00:15:42,039
"The Lord is my Shepherd,

211
00:15:42,107 --> 00:15:44,302
<i>I shall not want. "</i>

212
00:15:44,376 --> 00:15:47,368
<i>[Ninny] Oh, it like
to have killed us all.</i>

213
00:15:47,446 --> 00:15:50,108
<i>But nary a one took it
as hard as Idgie,</i>

214
00:15:53,218 --> 00:15:58,679
<i>everyone thought she'd die
right along with him.</i>

215
00:16:04,496 --> 00:16:07,863
[Sobbing]

216
00:16:15,341 --> 00:16:19,607
<i>Night after night,
she stayed by the river.</i>

217
00:16:19,678 --> 00:16:23,842
<i>Big George was the only soul
she'd let near her,</i>

218
00:16:23,916 --> 00:16:27,443
<i>and he watched over her
night and day.</i>

219
00:16:27,519 --> 00:16:30,317
<i>You know,
a heart can be broken,</i>

220
00:16:30,389 --> 00:16:33,449
<i>but it still keeps a-beatin'
Just the same.</i>

221
00:16:33,525 --> 00:16:36,153
Miss Idgie, you'll have
to keep this blanket on...

222
00:16:36,228 --> 00:16:39,129
or you'll catch your death
of cold, you hear me now?

223
00:16:39,198 --> 00:16:43,601
That's so sad.

224
00:16:49,008 --> 00:16:51,602
Ah.

225
00:16:51,677 --> 00:16:53,668
Would you like
one of these?

226
00:16:53,746 --> 00:16:55,737
Oh, thank ya,
honey.

227
00:16:55,814 --> 00:16:57,679
<i>[Ed]
Evelyn?</i>

228
00:16:57,750 --> 00:16:59,911
Honey,
we gotta get goin'.

229
00:16:59,985 --> 00:17:02,385
The Braves' game's
fixin' to start...

230
00:17:02,454 --> 00:17:04,081
and you're gonna miss
your... thing.

231
00:17:04,156 --> 00:17:07,887
Excuse me.
That's my husband, Ed.

232
00:17:07,960 --> 00:17:10,019
Hi, ma'am.
How you doin'?

233
00:17:10,095 --> 00:17:13,531
Um,

234
00:17:13,599 --> 00:17:15,658
I can't believe
Buddy died.

235
00:17:15,734 --> 00:17:18,328
Neither could I.

236
00:17:18,404 --> 00:17:21,805
Oh, well, I enjoyed
talkin' to you, honey.

237
00:17:21,874 --> 00:17:23,865
What's your name?

238
00:17:23,942 --> 00:17:27,002
Evelyn...
Evelyn Couch.

239
00:17:27,079 --> 00:17:31,846
I've got to go. You come
back and see me, you hear?

240
00:17:31,917 --> 00:17:35,819
Okay.
Bye-bye.

241
00:17:36,021 --> 00:17:38,285
<i>[Woman] First of all, I want you...</i>

242
00:17:38,357 --> 00:17:40,951
<i>to truly
dedicate yourselves...</i>

243
00:17:41,026 --> 00:17:45,053
<i>to finding little ways to
putting that magic, that spark...</i>

244
00:17:45,130 --> 00:17:47,325
back into your marriage.

245
00:17:47,399 --> 00:17:51,335
When we think of
romance and marriage,

246
00:17:51,403 --> 00:17:55,430
<i>what is the first thought that
comes into your mind? Divorce!</i>

247
00:17:55,507 --> 00:17:59,204
Remember when counselors used to tell
you to wrap yourself in cellophane...

248
00:17:59,278 --> 00:18:01,473
to put a little charge
into your marriage?

249
00:18:01,547 --> 00:18:04,345
Do we really pay
for these lectures?

250
00:18:04,416 --> 00:18:07,112
<i>You can see,
it is truly up to you...</i>

251
00:18:07,186 --> 00:18:10,678
<i>to put romance back
into your relationship.</i>

252
00:18:10,756 --> 00:18:15,216
<i>["What Becomes
Of The Brokenhearted"]</i>

253
00:18:17,729 --> 00:18:20,197
<i>Oh, yeah</i>

254
00:18:20,265 --> 00:18:23,462
<i>Da-na-na
da-na-na-na</i>

255
00:18:23,535 --> 00:18:28,598
<i>As I walk this land
of broken dreams</i>

256
00:18:28,674 --> 00:18:33,111
<i>I have visions
of many things</i>

257
00:18:33,178 --> 00:18:36,272
<i>Happiness
Hi, honey.</i>

258
00:18:36,348 --> 00:18:38,316
<i>Is just an illusion</i>

259
00:18:38,383 --> 00:18:40,351
Evelyn,
have you gone insane?

260
00:18:40,419 --> 00:18:42,353
<i>My God,
people can see you!</i>

261
00:18:42,421 --> 00:18:44,480
<i>What if I had been
the paperboy?</i>

262
00:18:44,556 --> 00:18:46,319
Get in there!

263
00:18:46,391 --> 00:18:49,189
<i>What are you
thinking about?</i>

264
00:18:49,995 --> 00:18:53,328
<i>Evelyn?</i>

265
00:18:53,398 --> 00:18:55,696
Evelyn!
Oh.

266
00:18:55,767 --> 00:18:59,726
You know, what we really need
instead of this baloney...

267
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:03,866
is an assertiveness training
class for Southern women.

268
00:19:03,942 --> 00:19:07,503
But that's a contradiction
in terms, isn't it?

269
00:19:07,579 --> 00:19:10,810
Especially you, sweetheart.
You're livin' in the Dark Ages.

270
00:19:12,651 --> 00:19:17,884
<i>The roots of love
grow all around</i>

271
00:19:17,956 --> 00:19:22,791
<i>But the leaves
they come tumblin'down</i>

272
00:19:22,861 --> 00:19:27,889
<i>Every day, heartaches
grow a little stronger</i>

273
00:19:27,966 --> 00:19:32,960
<i>I can't stand this pain
much longer</i>

274
00:19:34,072 --> 00:19:36,666
Hi, honey. I need one of those. Hi!

275
00:19:36,742 --> 00:19:39,506
Mmm, you smell good too.

276
00:19:39,578 --> 00:19:41,603
I need one of these.

277
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:44,615
Oh, this looks good! Uh-huh.

278
00:19:44,683 --> 00:19:46,617
Yes, indeedy.

279
00:19:46,685 --> 00:19:51,748
<i>Always movin'
but goin'nowhere</i>

280
00:19:51,823 --> 00:19:55,725
<i>[TV: Indistinct]</i>

281
00:19:55,794 --> 00:19:58,763
Ed.

282
00:20:00,465 --> 00:20:02,626
<i>Why don't you come in
and sit down at the table...</i>

283
00:20:02,701 --> 00:20:06,637
and have dinner with me? I'm
sorry. The game's almost over.

284
00:20:06,705 --> 00:20:09,538
I just want to see a little bit
of it. Why you so dressed up?

285
00:20:09,608 --> 00:20:12,099
Honey, don't get in the way.
Scoot over a bit.

286
00:20:12,177 --> 00:20:14,111
[Sigh]

287
00:20:16,248 --> 00:20:17,806
Ed?

288
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:20,875
If I'd answered the door
wearing only cellophane,

289
00:20:20,953 --> 00:20:24,252
would you still be
watching the baseball game?

290
00:20:24,323 --> 00:20:28,054
No, honey. I'd probably be
checking you into a looney bin.

291
00:20:50,382 --> 00:20:54,614
<i>[Knocking]
Hi, sugar.</i>

292
00:20:54,686 --> 00:20:56,620
<i>How's my dumplin'?
Trick or treat!</i>

293
00:20:56,688 --> 00:20:58,622
<i>[Ed] You're not gonna throw
them hissy-fits, are you?</i>

294
00:20:58,690 --> 00:21:01,921
<i>[Evelyn] Happy Halloween!
Oh, no. No, no, no!</i>

295
00:21:01,994 --> 00:21:04,087
<i>[Ed] You're meaner than a damn snake.</i>

296
00:21:04,162 --> 00:21:06,153
I'm glad
you're feeling better.

297
00:21:06,231 --> 00:21:09,462
<i>Get back in bed. Good thing
your eyesight's failing.</i>

298
00:21:19,111 --> 00:21:22,239
Hey!
Mmm. Oh.

299
00:21:22,314 --> 00:21:25,715
Hey. I was hopin' you'd be here.

300
00:21:25,784 --> 00:21:29,845
My roommate, Mrs. Otis,
said I could visit her family,

301
00:21:29,921 --> 00:21:31,855
but I said,
"Thank you kindly,

302
00:21:31,923 --> 00:21:34,551
but I think I might have
my own visitor."

303
00:21:34,626 --> 00:21:36,617
And here you are.

304
00:21:36,695 --> 00:21:38,959
Well, sit down.
Thank you.

305
00:21:39,031 --> 00:21:42,558
And doughnuts to boot!
You can't beat that.

306
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:45,467
Well, help yourself, Mrs.
Threadgoode. Thank you.

307
00:21:46,204 --> 00:21:47,228
How's your friend?

308
00:21:47,306 --> 00:21:49,297
Mrs. Otis?
Uh-huh.

309
00:21:49,374 --> 00:21:52,309
Well, not so good.
Oh.

310
00:21:52,377 --> 00:21:55,107
Looks like I won't be
gettin' home for quite a while,

311
00:21:55,180 --> 00:21:58,616
and I sure miss it.

312
00:21:58,684 --> 00:22:01,949
Funny what you miss
when you're away from home.

313
00:22:02,020 --> 00:22:04,420
I miss
the smell of coffee...

314
00:22:04,489 --> 00:22:07,287
and bacon fryin'.

315
00:22:07,359 --> 00:22:11,853
Oh, what I wouldn't give for a
plate of fried green tomatoes...

316
00:22:11,930 --> 00:22:14,626
like we used to have
at the cafe.

317
00:22:14,700 --> 00:22:17,100
Ooh!

318
00:22:20,639 --> 00:22:23,699
I never told you about the cafe, did I?

319
00:22:23,775 --> 00:22:25,709
No, ma'am.

320
00:22:25,777 --> 00:22:30,373
Oh, well...
now let me back up a bit.

321
00:22:30,449 --> 00:22:35,682
<i>[Ninny] You see, Idgie never
quite got over losing Buddy.</i>

322
00:22:38,023 --> 00:22:41,083
<i>She hardly
ever come home.</i>

323
00:22:41,159 --> 00:22:44,026
<i>Only Big George
knew how to find her.</i>

324
00:22:44,096 --> 00:22:48,829
<i>She just didn't seem to care
about anythin'anymore.</i>

325
00:22:48,900 --> 00:22:50,834
<i>Then, one summer day,</i>

326
00:22:50,902 --> 00:22:53,871
<i>her mama sent for her.</i>

327
00:22:53,939 --> 00:22:55,873
<i>Like they say,</i>

328
00:22:55,941 --> 00:22:59,433
<i>God never shuts one door
without opening another.</i>

329
00:22:59,511 --> 00:23:03,140
<i>That was also the day Idgie
met Frank Bennett, Mama!</i>

330
00:23:03,215 --> 00:23:05,945
<i>The man whose murder
got her arrested.</i>

331
00:23:06,017 --> 00:23:10,044
Well, hello there, miss.
And who might you be?

332
00:23:11,123 --> 00:23:13,614
Towanda to you.
Who are you?

333
00:23:13,692 --> 00:23:17,924
Oh, Frank Bennett's
the name, Miss Towanda.

334
00:23:17,996 --> 00:23:21,989
I must say you are lookin'
mighty fine today.

335
00:23:22,067 --> 00:23:24,058
You a politician...

336
00:23:24,136 --> 00:23:27,333
or does lying
just run in your family?

337
00:23:28,673 --> 00:23:31,335
<i>[Idgie]
Mama!</i>

338
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:33,275
Well, there you are!

339
00:23:33,345 --> 00:23:36,337
<i>Well, it's about time,
Idgie.</i>

340
00:23:39,151 --> 00:23:42,052
If you don't look like
the wild man of Borneo.

341
00:23:42,120 --> 00:23:45,715
Here you go. Well, thank you.

342
00:23:45,791 --> 00:23:48,123
Guess who's here?
Who?

343
00:23:48,193 --> 00:23:50,855
Ruth. She's stayin'
with us this summer...

344
00:23:50,929 --> 00:23:54,330
and will be in charge of all the young
people's activities at the church.

345
00:23:54,399 --> 00:23:59,166
Is that why you wanted to see me?
We have so many things planned.

346
00:23:59,237 --> 00:24:01,364
<i>Ruth?</i>

347
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:04,932
<i>You remember my youngest
child? Of course I do.</i>

348
00:24:05,010 --> 00:24:06,944
Hi, Idgie.

349
00:24:08,513 --> 00:24:11,004
Hi.

350
00:24:14,586 --> 00:24:17,783
Maybe this isn't
such a good idea.

351
00:24:17,856 --> 00:24:20,416
Oh, it's got to work.

352
00:24:20,492 --> 00:24:23,984
<i>Somebody's got to help her. I can't.</i>

353
00:24:24,696 --> 00:24:28,359
[Big George] Are you sure you want
to go to this river club, Miss Ruth?

354
00:24:28,433 --> 00:24:30,367
These ain't no
churchgoing folks.

355
00:24:30,435 --> 00:24:33,666
<i>[Ruth] I'll do just
fine, George, thank you.</i>

356
00:24:33,738 --> 00:24:36,172
Oh, excuse me.

357
00:24:36,241 --> 00:24:39,540
Is Idgie Threadgoode here
by any chance?

358
00:24:39,611 --> 00:24:42,409
Come on in, honey.
She's right down here.

359
00:24:42,481 --> 00:24:45,917
Here? Okay.
Uh-huh.

360
00:24:45,984 --> 00:24:48,612
I'll see you,
Grady Kilgore,

361
00:24:48,687 --> 00:24:50,746
and I'll
raise you twenty.

362
00:24:50,822 --> 00:24:53,382
You ain't got nothin'!

363
00:24:53,458 --> 00:24:56,757
<i>[Idgie] Maybe I do and maybe I don't.</i>

364
00:24:56,828 --> 00:25:01,060
Put your money where
your mouth is, Mr. Sheriff.

365
00:25:05,103 --> 00:25:07,731
Well, look what
the cat drug in!

366
00:25:07,806 --> 00:25:11,674
I came to talk to you.

367
00:25:11,743 --> 00:25:14,109
You're gonna have to wait.
I'm busy.

368
00:25:14,179 --> 00:25:16,773
Come on, Grady, this is your
big chance. You in or out?

369
00:25:16,848 --> 00:25:19,282
<i>I'll make you
a rich man.</i>

370
00:25:19,351 --> 00:25:22,343
<i>[Grady] You just bluffin'again as usual.</i>

371
00:25:22,420 --> 00:25:25,412
I'm afraid you're gonna have to excuse
Idgie. She's goin' home for dinner.

372
00:25:25,490 --> 00:25:27,651
Say good-bye, Idgie.
Where you goin'?

373
00:25:27,726 --> 00:25:32,095
Where the hell you goin' with
my money? We're goin' home!

374
00:25:32,163 --> 00:25:36,099
<i>- Who are you to boss me around?
- The one holdin' your money!</i>

375
00:25:36,167 --> 00:25:38,101
Give it back.

376
00:25:38,169 --> 00:25:40,296
Now, get in the car.

377
00:25:42,173 --> 00:25:45,404
All right,
I'll get in the car.

378
00:25:45,477 --> 00:25:47,968
You win!

379
00:25:48,046 --> 00:25:51,015
Come on.

380
00:25:51,082 --> 00:25:52,640
Sucker!

381
00:25:52,717 --> 00:25:54,742
<i>[Idgie]
I'll leave when I want!</i>

382
00:25:54,819 --> 00:25:58,619
I don't know how you can break
your mother's heart like you do.

383
00:25:58,690 --> 00:26:00,851
I'm not doin' anything
to my mother.

384
00:26:00,926 --> 00:26:03,486
Oh, no? Why do you think
I'm here for the summer?

385
00:26:03,562 --> 00:26:06,929
Your mother was so worried, she thought I
might be able to talk some sense into you.

386
00:26:06,998 --> 00:26:09,330
<i>But you're too busy
being selfish!</i>

387
00:26:09,401 --> 00:26:12,370
What are you
talkin' about?

388
00:26:12,437 --> 00:26:16,134
You're not the only one
who lost Buddy.

389
00:26:16,207 --> 00:26:18,300
We all miss him...

390
00:26:18,376 --> 00:26:21,243
but turning your back on
your family is not gonna help.

391
00:26:23,615 --> 00:26:25,674
What's he got to do
with anything?

392
00:26:25,750 --> 00:26:29,880
<i>Looks like you're the one with
the problem forgetting my brother.</i>

393
00:26:34,259 --> 00:26:36,750
<i>[Rev. Scroggins]
Why, just ten miles away...</i>

394
00:26:36,828 --> 00:26:38,728
<i>down by the river,</i>

395
00:26:38,797 --> 00:26:41,027
<i>there lurks
a den of the devil...</i>

396
00:26:41,099 --> 00:26:44,933
<i>where liquor
and gamblin'...</i>

397
00:26:45,003 --> 00:26:47,836
<i>and sin abide!</i>

398
00:26:47,906 --> 00:26:51,569
Snakes and serpents...

399
00:26:51,643 --> 00:26:53,804
<i>[Honking] [Idgie] Hey, Scroggins!</i>

400
00:26:53,878 --> 00:26:57,837
You're finally preachin' about
somethin' you're kin to... snakes!

401
00:26:57,916 --> 00:27:01,215
<i>[Laughing] [Rev. Scroggins] As I said,</i>

402
00:27:01,286 --> 00:27:06,417
snakes and serpents
take many disguises.

403
00:27:06,491 --> 00:27:09,756
<i>Let's turn to page 53
in our hymnal.</i>

404
00:27:15,867 --> 00:27:18,859
Yoo-hoo!

405
00:27:18,937 --> 00:27:23,738
Big George thought
I might find you here.

406
00:27:23,808 --> 00:27:26,538
[Chuckle]

407
00:27:26,611 --> 00:27:31,446
If you give me a chance,
a chance to get to know you,

408
00:27:31,516 --> 00:27:35,247
maybe it'll be fun!

409
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:38,721
Fun?

410
00:27:38,790 --> 00:27:42,055
Idgie, just spend
some time with me.

411
00:27:42,127 --> 00:27:44,061
Please?

412
00:27:44,129 --> 00:27:46,063
Suit yourself.

413
00:27:46,765 --> 00:27:49,427
<i>[Idgie] You sure you
don't wanna back out?</i>

414
00:27:49,501 --> 00:27:52,698
It's not too late.
I'm sure.

415
00:27:52,771 --> 00:27:55,103
Here, hold this.

416
00:27:57,108 --> 00:27:59,804
Tell me now,
you like trains?

417
00:27:59,878 --> 00:28:03,678
Yes.
Good.

418
00:28:03,748 --> 00:28:07,650
We'll get along
just fine!

419
00:28:09,154 --> 00:28:12,646
Boy, did we
luck out tonight.

420
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:17,757
Hop in.

421
00:28:17,829 --> 00:28:20,354
Hop?

422
00:28:20,432 --> 00:28:23,458
Oh. Give me
your hand.

423
00:28:23,535 --> 00:28:26,003
Put your foot
up there.

424
00:28:35,313 --> 00:28:37,440
Hold that.

425
00:28:38,349 --> 00:28:41,147
Ooo-ooo!
Look at all this!

426
00:28:41,219 --> 00:28:45,679
[Engine Chugging]

427
00:28:45,757 --> 00:28:49,318
Don't you think we should get off
the train? It's startin' to move.

428
00:28:49,394 --> 00:28:53,194
No. The fun
just started!

429
00:28:56,534 --> 00:28:58,934
You all right?

430
00:28:59,003 --> 00:29:03,235
Well, sometimes I get
a little dizzy lookin' down.

431
00:29:03,308 --> 00:29:06,004
Don't look down.

432
00:29:18,890 --> 00:29:22,656
What are you doin'?
Come on. Look.

433
00:29:22,727 --> 00:29:25,628
<i>They're throwin'
away food!</i>

434
00:29:25,697 --> 00:29:28,029
[Shouting]

435
00:29:29,467 --> 00:29:32,095
You talk about
"give unto others."

436
00:29:32,170 --> 00:29:35,230
Yes, but this food
isn't yours to give.

437
00:29:35,306 --> 00:29:37,467
That's church talk.

438
00:29:37,542 --> 00:29:40,534
I've seen those same people
over at church on Sunday...

439
00:29:40,612 --> 00:29:43,240
over at the river club every
other night of the week,

440
00:29:43,314 --> 00:29:47,182
doin' anything
but pray. Come on.

441
00:29:49,587 --> 00:29:52,613
<i>[Indistinct Chatter]</i>

442
00:30:03,101 --> 00:30:04,728
<i>More!
Give me some.</i>

443
00:30:30,061 --> 00:30:33,428
Okay, time to get off.

444
00:30:34,065 --> 00:30:36,033
We gotta jump.

445
00:30:36,100 --> 00:30:38,694
Jump?

446
00:30:38,770 --> 00:30:41,830
<i>Yeah, jump. The next stop's
five miles down the tracks.</i>

447
00:30:41,906 --> 00:30:43,897
I don't wanna walk
that far back.

448
00:30:43,975 --> 00:30:46,842
Are you crazy?

449
00:30:46,911 --> 00:30:49,277
<i>You're not kiddin'.</i>

450
00:30:49,347 --> 00:30:53,010
Well...

451
00:30:53,084 --> 00:30:55,552
I give up. Jump.

452
00:30:55,620 --> 00:30:58,885
I'll tell Mama I'm not
a good influence on you...

453
00:30:58,957 --> 00:31:01,221
You'll never jump,
will you?

454
00:31:03,261 --> 00:31:06,389
Don't say "never"
to me.

455
00:31:16,007 --> 00:31:18,373
[Scream]

456
00:31:18,443 --> 00:31:21,207
Towanda!

457
00:31:34,092 --> 00:31:36,686
<i>You all right?
I'm fine.</i>

458
00:31:36,761 --> 00:31:40,322
<i>I'm all right.</i>

459
00:31:40,398 --> 00:31:42,525
Ow!

460
00:31:42,600 --> 00:31:44,932
Does this hurt?
[Gasp]

461
00:31:45,003 --> 00:31:47,767
Guess so.

462
00:31:47,839 --> 00:31:50,137
We better get you to
a doc... doctor. Shit!

463
00:31:50,208 --> 00:31:52,301
Which way is it?

464
00:31:52,377 --> 00:31:55,972
About two miles
down the tracks.

465
00:31:56,047 --> 00:31:58,277
All right,
let's go.

466
00:32:00,084 --> 00:32:03,576
You'll never be able
to carry me that far.

467
00:32:03,655 --> 00:32:06,351
I know.
Never say never.

468
