She said her husband...

1165
01:25:23,551 --> 01:25:25,849
will just be watching
his sports on TV...

1166
01:25:25,920 --> 01:25:29,083
and she has an urge to hit him
in the head with a baseball bat.

1167
01:25:29,157 --> 01:25:32,024
Hell, that
seems normal to me.

1168
01:25:32,093 --> 01:25:34,084
<i>Hi, Janeen.
Mm-hmm.</i>

1169
01:25:34,162 --> 01:25:36,630
Mrs. Threadgoode, would
you like some crudites?

1170
01:25:36,698 --> 01:25:41,101
Thank you, but this raw stuff
don't sit good with me.

1171
01:25:41,169 --> 01:25:45,333
Mrs. Threadgoode, you
have to tell me something.

1172
01:25:45,406 --> 01:25:50,173
Did Idgie murder Frank Bennett
or not? Hold your horses, honey.

1173
01:25:50,245 --> 01:25:53,271
Where were we?

1174
01:25:53,348 --> 01:25:56,078
You didn't kill Ed,
did ya?

1175
01:25:56,151 --> 01:25:59,814
Not yet.
Oh, good.

1176
01:25:59,888 --> 01:26:04,552
Anyway, five years had passed
since Frank Bennett disappeared.

1177
01:26:04,626 --> 01:26:09,325
<i>[Ninny] And Smokey Lonesome been
missin'ever since that same terrible night.</i>

1178
01:26:09,397 --> 01:26:12,457
<i>I 'member the day
when he showed up again.</i>

1179
01:26:13,401 --> 01:26:15,369
My God, son,

1180
01:26:15,436 --> 01:26:17,597
you're the spittin'
image of Ruth.

1181
01:26:17,672 --> 01:26:21,005
Buddy Threadgoode, Jr.
Nice to meet you, sir.

1182
01:26:21,075 --> 01:26:23,441
Well, sir,
Smokey Lonesome.

1183
01:26:23,511 --> 01:26:26,708
<i>[Ninny] Curtis Smoote was making one
of his visits to Whistle Stop, Alabama,</i>

1184
01:26:26,781 --> 01:26:29,579
<i>still huntin'and peckin'
for any scrap of evidence...</i>

1185
01:26:29,651 --> 01:26:32,677
<i>about Frank Bennett's
whereabouts.</i>

1186
01:26:32,754 --> 01:26:35,245
<i>[Ruth] Who wants to begin? Oh, I do.</i>

1187
01:26:35,323 --> 01:26:37,154
<i>I do, Miss Ruth.
Thank you.</i>

1188
01:26:37,225 --> 01:26:40,490
We'll begin
on page five.

1189
01:26:40,562 --> 01:26:43,827
<i>[Ninny] Life has a funny
way of working things out.</i>

1190
01:26:43,898 --> 01:26:45,729
Well, hey there!

1191
01:26:45,800 --> 01:26:49,361
<i>Smokey!
Idgie?</i>

1192
01:26:49,437 --> 01:26:52,964
Smokey Lonesome!
If it isn't old home week.

1193
01:26:53,041 --> 01:26:56,636
How are you? Well, I'm
rattlin' but I'm rollin'.

1194
01:26:56,711 --> 01:27:00,272
What brings you to these
parts? Smell of good cookin'.

1195
01:27:00,348 --> 01:27:01,940
Hey, Smokey.

1196
01:27:02,016 --> 01:27:05,076
Sipsey. Let me fix you some lunch.

1197
01:27:05,153 --> 01:27:09,556
You know just about everybody
except Curtis Smoote.

1198
01:27:09,624 --> 01:27:13,116
<i>He's the officer from
over at Valdosta, Georgia.</i>

1199
01:27:13,194 --> 01:27:17,290
He's been lookin' for the same man for
almost 5 years. Very stubborn fella.

1200
01:27:17,365 --> 01:27:21,301
<i>He loves our barbecue.</i>

1201
01:27:21,369 --> 01:27:22,700
<i>[Buddy, Jr.]
Mommy! Mommy!</i>

1202
01:27:23,404 --> 01:27:25,338
<i>[Screaming]</i>

1203
01:27:30,878 --> 01:27:32,812
<i>Buddy.</i>

1204
01:27:32,880 --> 01:27:34,814
Everybody
outta the way.

1205
01:27:34,882 --> 01:27:38,648
Give him here.
Let him go. I've got him.

1206
01:27:40,622 --> 01:27:42,817
Come on. You're
gonna be all right.

1207
01:27:42,890 --> 01:27:45,222
Open the door!

1208
01:27:45,293 --> 01:27:49,354
<i>[Idgie] Put him in the
car. It's all right, honey.</i>

1209
01:27:53,968 --> 01:27:57,529
<i>["Taps"]</i>

1210
01:28:10,585 --> 01:28:12,485
<i>[Ruth]
I can understand...</i>

1211
01:28:12,553 --> 01:28:15,078
having a funeral
for an arm.

1212
01:28:15,156 --> 01:28:18,683
I just don't know why she
insists on callin' him "Stump."

1213
01:28:18,760 --> 01:28:21,752
<i>[Sipsey] She say everybody
else gonna be callin'him that...</i>

1214
01:28:21,829 --> 01:28:25,925
so we might just as well
be the first.

1215
01:28:26,000 --> 01:28:30,164
Okay, ice cream
and cake for everybody.

1216
01:28:30,238 --> 01:28:32,035
Go on.

1217
01:28:36,311 --> 01:28:40,304
My daddy always used to say there
was a separate God for children.

1218
01:28:44,185 --> 01:28:47,712
<i>[Ninny] The good Lord was
watchin' over stump that day.</i>

1219
01:28:47,789 --> 01:28:51,156
<i>But then it started to rain
that month.</i>

1220
01:28:51,225 --> 01:28:56,060
<i>It rained and rained, and it
flooded parts of Whistle Stop.</i>

1221
01:28:56,130 --> 01:29:01,261
<i>That's why Grady's deputies stumbled
onto Frank Bennett's pickup truck,</i>

1222
01:29:01,336 --> 01:29:05,329
<i>and I just knew Idgie'd
never get out of this mess.</i>

1223
01:29:05,406 --> 01:29:09,172
Now, you in or out? Remember,
I didn't take any cards.

1224
01:29:09,243 --> 01:29:11,677
Look at me and
let me see your face.

1225
01:29:11,746 --> 01:29:13,976
Idgie, I have to talk
to you. You're bluffin'.

1226
01:29:14,048 --> 01:29:17,814
Why don't you sit in? I'll deal
you a new hand. Gladys won't mind.

1227
01:29:17,885 --> 01:29:19,978
In private, Idgie.

1228
01:29:20,054 --> 01:29:23,080
Excuse us, Ruth.

1229
01:29:23,157 --> 01:29:27,423
A-ha. I'm just tryin' to teach
you not to fall for any tricks.

1230
01:29:27,495 --> 01:29:30,123
You're doin'
a great job.

1231
01:29:38,940 --> 01:29:41,170
What's your hurry?

1232
01:29:41,242 --> 01:29:44,473
And what is
so important?

1233
01:29:44,545 --> 01:29:46,775
What's that?

1234
01:29:46,848 --> 01:29:50,181
<i>[Grady] Somebody found Frank
Bennett's truck in the river.</i>

1235
01:29:50,251 --> 01:29:53,414
What's that got
to do with me?

1236
01:29:53,488 --> 01:29:57,447
Officially, you and Big George
are under arrest for murder.

1237
01:29:57,525 --> 01:30:00,426
You're in my custody
until tomorrow.

1238
01:30:00,495 --> 01:30:03,191
I'm supposed to take you to
Georgia first thing in the morning.

1239
01:30:05,266 --> 01:30:07,461
<i>Unless, of course...</i>

1240
01:30:07,535 --> 01:30:10,265
Well, some people have
been known to pack up...

1241
01:30:10,338 --> 01:30:14,741
and sneak out of town
in the middle of the night.

1242
01:30:16,477 --> 01:30:19,037
<i>[Idgie]
What about Big George?</i>

1243
01:30:19,113 --> 01:30:21,843
Well, the way
I figure it,

1244
01:30:21,916 --> 01:30:25,147
they'd be satisfied
if they had him.

1245
01:30:25,219 --> 01:30:27,278
Idgie,
this is serious.

1246
01:30:27,355 --> 01:30:29,949
We're talkin'
murder of a white man.

1247
01:30:30,024 --> 01:30:32,254
Someone's
gonna have to pay.

1248
01:30:32,326 --> 01:30:35,159
Nobody wants
to hang a woman.

1249
01:30:36,697 --> 01:30:38,688
No deal.

1250
01:30:38,766 --> 01:30:41,360
Idgie, I know how you feel
about Big George.

1251
01:30:41,436 --> 01:30:43,563
Hell, we all do.

1252
01:30:43,638 --> 01:30:46,801
But these just
the facts of life.

1253
01:30:49,243 --> 01:30:51,507
I can't do that.

1254
01:30:51,579 --> 01:30:54,343
Take me to jail
if you have to.

1255
01:30:54,415 --> 01:30:56,906
Well, that's what
I thought you'd say...

1256
01:30:56,984 --> 01:30:59,384
'cause you're absolutely,
unconditionally,

1257
01:30:59,454 --> 01:31:03,948
<i>positively the most stubborn
person I've known in my life.</i>

1258
01:31:05,793 --> 01:31:10,492
<i>[Ninny] Idgie and Big George went
to the county jail in Valdosta...</i>

1259
01:31:10,565 --> 01:31:14,365
<i>to await trial for
the murder of Frank Bennett.</i>

1260
01:31:14,435 --> 01:31:16,562
<i>They didn't have
to wait too long.</i>

1261
01:31:16,637 --> 01:31:20,038
Did you know Frank Bennett? No, sir.

1262
01:31:20,107 --> 01:31:22,507
You mean, you
never met the man...

1263
01:31:22,577 --> 01:31:27,105
<i>whose wife, Ruth, is your
business partner? That's right.</i>

1264
01:31:27,181 --> 01:31:30,014
You never threatened to kill
Frank Bennett at his home...

1265
01:31:30,084 --> 01:31:33,781
in front of his hired man
in June of 1932?

1266
01:31:33,855 --> 01:31:38,883
<i>The same Frank Bennett you did not
know. Oh, that was me, all right.</i>

1267
01:31:38,960 --> 01:31:42,191
<i>I thought you wanted to know if we'd
ever met... and the answer is no.</i>

1268
01:31:42,263 --> 01:31:44,823
<i>Um, I threatened
to kill him,</i>

1269
01:31:44,899 --> 01:31:49,063
<i>but we were never, what you
might say, properly introduced.</i>

1270
01:31:49,136 --> 01:31:53,129
Is it not true that in September
of 1932 you came to Valdosta...

1271
01:31:53,207 --> 01:31:57,041
<i>and took Frank Bennett's wife and
child back to Alabama with you?</i>

1272
01:31:57,111 --> 01:31:59,579
Um... just the wife.
The child came later.

1273
01:31:59,647 --> 01:32:03,105
How much later? The usual. Nine months.

1274
01:32:03,184 --> 01:32:06,051
<i>[Laughter] I suggest that you bribed...</i>

1275
01:32:06,120 --> 01:32:11,422
this poor, weak woman with
promises of liquor and money,

1276
01:32:11,492 --> 01:32:15,223
and she lost control
of her senses momentarily.

1277
01:32:15,296 --> 01:32:18,288
When her husband came back
to get her and take her home,

1278
01:32:18,366 --> 01:32:22,996
you and your colored man
murdered him in cold blood.

1279
01:32:24,205 --> 01:32:25,797
No, sir.

1280
01:32:25,873 --> 01:32:31,140
Well, where were you on the
night of September 30, 1933?

1281
01:32:31,212 --> 01:32:33,510
I was at the town hall
doing a show.

1282
01:32:33,581 --> 01:32:36,675
And after that? I was
at my mother's house.

1283
01:32:36,751 --> 01:32:39,276
Oh, yeah?
Who was with you?

1284
01:32:39,353 --> 01:32:43,687
<i>Just Big George and myself. What about
your mother? Can she confirm that?</i>

1285
01:32:43,758 --> 01:32:46,022
No, sir.
She died a year ago.

1286
01:32:46,093 --> 01:32:48,584
I'm sorry to hear that.

1287
01:32:48,663 --> 01:32:52,360
But do you expect 12 intelligent
men to believe you,

1288
01:32:52,433 --> 01:32:55,061
although one witness is dead and
the other is a colored man,

1289
01:32:55,136 --> 01:32:58,537
known to be a worthless,
no-good, lying nigger?

1290
01:32:58,606 --> 01:33:00,870
You expect these men
to take your word for it...

1291
01:33:00,942 --> 01:33:03,604
<i>Just because
you say so?</i>

1292
01:33:03,678 --> 01:33:08,206
That's right, you gump-faced,
blown-up, baboon-assed bastard!

1293
01:33:08,282 --> 01:33:11,740
<i>[Gasping] One more outburst like that...</i>

1294
01:33:11,819 --> 01:33:15,311
and I'll hold you in contempt
of court. You understand?

1295
01:33:15,389 --> 01:33:18,187
Yes, sir.

1296
01:33:19,894 --> 01:33:23,455
Oh, Lord.
Next witness.

1297
01:33:26,033 --> 01:33:27,500
<i>[Prosecutor] Did you know
that you were pregnant...</i>

1298
01:33:27,568 --> 01:33:30,503
<i>at the time
you left Valdosta?</i>

1299
01:33:30,571 --> 01:33:32,505
<i>[Ruth]
Yes.</i>

1300
01:33:32,573 --> 01:33:36,168
<i>And yet, you tell us
over and over...</i>

1301
01:33:36,243 --> 01:33:40,805
<i>that you went with this
woman... willingly?</i>

1302
01:33:40,881 --> 01:33:45,079
Yes. I wouldn't raise
my child with Frank Bennett.

1303
01:33:45,152 --> 01:33:47,245
<i>But why?</i>

1304
01:33:47,321 --> 01:33:51,519
<i>Did this woman promise you money? No.</i>

1305
01:33:51,592 --> 01:33:54,152
<i>A bigger home?</i>

1306
01:33:54,228 --> 01:33:57,322
No. No.

1307
01:33:57,398 --> 01:34:00,026
<i>Then tell us,
Mrs. Bennett,</i>

1308
01:34:00,101 --> 01:34:02,626
<i>why would a respectable
Christian woman...</i>

1309
01:34:02,703 --> 01:34:05,501
<i>go anywhere with this Idgie
Threadgoode... I object.</i>

1310
01:34:05,573 --> 01:34:07,700
<i>Whose reputation
is known far and wide...</i>

1311
01:34:07,775 --> 01:34:10,005
<i>as a notorious liar
and drunkard?</i>

1312
01:34:10,077 --> 01:34:12,375
<i>- Objection!
- Sustained!</i>

1313
01:34:15,783 --> 01:34:18,081
<i>Why did you leave...</i>

1314
01:34:18,152 --> 01:34:22,111
<i>with Idgie Threadgoode
that day?</i>

1315
01:34:23,524 --> 01:34:26,823
<i>[Judge] Answer the
question, Mrs. Bennett.</i>

1316
01:34:27,695 --> 01:34:30,721
Because she...

1317
01:34:33,300 --> 01:34:35,894
She's the best friend
I ever had,

1318
01:34:35,970 --> 01:34:38,063
and I love her.

1319
01:34:38,773 --> 01:34:41,674
<i>[Prosecutor] Thank you, Mrs.
Bennett. That will be all.</i>

1320
01:34:41,742 --> 01:34:44,575
<i>[Defense Attorney] The defense
calls as its last witness...</i>

1321
01:34:44,645 --> 01:34:47,375
<i>the Rev.
Herbert Scroggins.</i>

1322
01:34:48,716 --> 01:34:51,708
Place your right hand
on the Bible, please.

1323
01:34:51,786 --> 01:34:54,983
I brought my own,
if you don't mind.

1324
01:34:55,056 --> 01:34:59,117
You swear to tell the whole
truth and nothing but the truth?

1325
01:34:59,193 --> 01:35:01,184
I do.

1326
01:35:03,230 --> 01:35:07,462
<i>[Defense Attorney] You have
information about the whereabouts...</i>

1327
01:35:07,535 --> 01:35:11,130
<i>of Idgie Threadgoode and her
colored man, known as Big George,</i>

1328
01:35:11,205 --> 01:35:14,971
on the night
of September 30, 1933?

1329
01:35:15,042 --> 01:35:17,010
Yes, sir,
I do.

1330
01:35:17,078 --> 01:35:19,512
<i>It has been
suggested here...</i>

1331
01:35:19,580 --> 01:35:23,038
<i>that she and her colored man
were at her mother's house.</i>

1332
01:35:23,117 --> 01:35:27,349
<i>Can you confirm that?
No, sir. That is a lie.</i>

1333
01:35:27,421 --> 01:35:30,151
[Whispering]
Oh, shit.

1334
01:35:30,224 --> 01:35:33,455
<i>[Rev. Scroggins] It has been my
habit to write all the dates...</i>

1335
01:35:33,527 --> 01:35:36,462
<i>of the activities of
the church in my Bible.</i>

1336
01:35:36,530 --> 01:35:41,194
<i>I show that the night
of September 30, 1933...</i>

1337
01:35:41,268 --> 01:35:44,294
was the start of our
annual revival...

1338
01:35:44,371 --> 01:35:47,135
down at the
Baptist campground.

1339
01:35:47,208 --> 01:35:49,301
Sister Threadgoode
was there...

1340
01:35:49,376 --> 01:35:53,403
<i>along with her hired man,
George Pullman,</i>

1341
01:35:53,481 --> 01:35:57,611
who was in charge of the
barbecue as he has been...

1342
01:35:57,685 --> 01:36:00,347
<i>for the last ten years.
Objection.</i>

1343
01:36:00,421 --> 01:36:04,949
That doesn't mean anything. Murder could've
taken place any time the next couple of days.

1344
01:36:05,025 --> 01:36:10,053
<i>Have you ever been to one of
our revivals, sir? Well, no.</i>

1345
01:36:10,131 --> 01:36:12,190
Do you attend church
regularly, sir?

1346
01:36:12,266 --> 01:36:14,461
'Course I do.

1347
01:36:14,535 --> 01:36:19,063
<i>Good. Well, maybe if you
attended one of our revivals,</i>

1348
01:36:19,140 --> 01:36:21,506
<i>you'd know
they last three days...</i>

1349
01:36:21,575 --> 01:36:23,907
and three nights,
Your Honor.

1350
01:36:24,645 --> 01:36:26,112
<i>[Gavel Pounding]</i>

1351
01:36:26,180 --> 01:36:29,149
<i>[Judge]
Approach the bench.</i>

1352
01:36:29,216 --> 01:36:33,915
Percy, it don't look like
you got a case at all.

1353
01:36:33,988 --> 01:36:36,548
In the first place,
there's no body.

1354
01:36:36,624 --> 01:36:39,889
Second, we got us a preacher
nobody's gonna dispute.

1355
01:36:39,960 --> 01:36:44,158
But, Your Honor... I'm tellin' you.
What you got is a lot of nothing.

1356
01:36:44,231 --> 01:36:47,462
<i>[Judge] I say Frank
Bennett got himself drunk,</i>

1357
01:36:47,535 --> 01:36:51,699
<i>drove into the river and
was long ago eaten up...</i>

1358
01:36:51,772 --> 01:36:54,935
and I don't give
a good goddamn!

1359
01:36:55,009 --> 01:36:58,467
What we got here is a
case of accidental death.

1360
01:36:58,546 --> 01:37:00,173
Case dismissed.

1361
01:37:00,247 --> 01:37:02,681
Whoo!

1362
01:37:09,623 --> 01:37:12,524
See you in church,
Sister?

1363
01:37:13,427 --> 01:37:15,657
Reverend.

1364
01:37:15,729 --> 01:37:20,029
I can't believe he
actually swore on a Bible.

1365
01:37:20,100 --> 01:37:22,034
Well, not really.

1366
01:37:22,102 --> 01:37:24,093
If that judge
had looked closer,

1367
01:37:24,171 --> 01:37:27,231
<i>he'd have seen it was really
a copy of Moby Dick.</i>

1368
01:37:29,276 --> 01:37:33,679
But why did he do it? For the sheer
joy of seeing you in church again...

1369
01:37:33,747 --> 01:37:36,580
which I suggested to him
might be your penance.

1370
01:37:36,650 --> 01:37:39,278
You didn't promise him,
did you? Yes, ma'am, I did.

1371
01:37:39,353 --> 01:37:41,287
And I never
break my word.

1372
01:37:41,355 --> 01:37:45,724
If I live 1,000 years,
I will never forgive you.

1373
01:37:45,793 --> 01:37:49,957
I don't know what's worse,
church or jail.

1374
01:38:00,941 --> 01:38:04,069
There now.
Don't you look pretty?

1375
01:38:04,144 --> 01:38:06,271
Oh, yes, honey.

1376
01:38:06,347 --> 01:38:11,011
You'll have me lookin' like
Ginger Rogers before you're done.

1377
01:38:11,085 --> 01:38:15,317
Don't let Mr. Dunaway see me.
He's liable to go wild.

1378
01:38:16,824 --> 01:38:20,055
I'm glad to see
you're in a good mood.

1379
01:38:20,127 --> 01:38:23,255
You've slimmed down quite a bit
in the last few weeks.

1380
01:38:23,330 --> 01:38:27,630
I'm just so happy Big George
and Idgie got off.

1381
01:38:27,701 --> 01:38:30,693
I would have killed Frank
Bennett if I could've.

1382
01:38:30,771 --> 01:38:33,296
Did anybody really
think she did it?

1383
01:38:33,374 --> 01:38:36,002
Some said yes,
some said no.

1384
01:38:36,076 --> 01:38:39,204
'Course the only one who really
knew was Frank Bennett.

1385
01:38:39,280 --> 01:38:44,684
And you know what they say.
Dead men tell no tales.

1386
01:38:45,352 --> 01:38:47,650
<i>[Evelyn]
Towanda-a-a!</i>

1387
01:38:47,721 --> 01:38:50,884
<i>[Grunting]</i>

1388
01:39:10,945 --> 01:39:13,971
Evelyn, what in the hell
are you doing?

1389
01:39:14,048 --> 01:39:16,949
I need some light
and air.

1390
01:39:17,017 --> 01:39:20,214
Why don't you take one of
your walks or your jog...

1391
01:39:20,287 --> 01:39:23,814
or whatever it is
you do?

1392
01:39:23,891 --> 01:39:26,792
There's no dinner
either!

1393
01:39:26,860 --> 01:39:31,297
Ed, you have any idea why I've
been goin' to all these classes?

1394
01:39:31,365 --> 01:39:34,892
<i>No. I've been trying
to save our marriage.</i>

1395
01:39:34,969 --> 01:39:36,994
What's the point
of my tryin'...

1396
01:39:37,071 --> 01:39:41,735
if you're gonna sit on
your butt drinking beer...

1397
01:39:41,809 --> 01:39:44,642
and watching baseball,
basketball, football...

1398
01:39:44,712 --> 01:39:47,840
bowling and hockey
and golf...

1399
01:39:47,915 --> 01:39:51,783
<i>and Challenge
of the Gladiators?</i>

1400
01:39:57,491 --> 01:40:02,019
<i>Mrs. Couch, I'm Sue,
Mrs. Otis'daughter-in-law.</i>

1401
01:40:02,096 --> 01:40:05,532
How are you? I've heard about
you from Mrs. Threadgoode.

1402
01:40:05,599 --> 01:40:09,296
She is so sweet. She's been
lookin' after my mother-in-law.

1403
01:40:09,370 --> 01:40:12,134
Now, how is Mrs. Otis doin', by the way?

1404
01:40:12,206 --> 01:40:16,666
Much better, thank you. It takes
time getting used to a strange place.

1405
01:40:16,744 --> 01:40:20,771
I'm glad to hear it. Mrs.
Threadgoode's been anxious to get home.

1406
01:40:20,848 --> 01:40:25,046
Mrs. Couch, Mrs. Threadgoode
doesn't have a house anymore.

1407
01:40:25,119 --> 01:40:28,577
They tore that down. What?

1408
01:40:28,655 --> 01:40:32,887
They had to. It was falling
apart, and it was condemned.

1409
01:40:32,960 --> 01:40:35,895
Oh, no.

1410
01:40:35,963 --> 01:40:40,161
<i>Does she know that? No, well, we
didn't see any point in telling her.</i>

1411
01:40:40,234 --> 01:40:42,725
<i>It would just break her heart,
poor old thing.</i>

1412
01:40:42,803 --> 01:40:46,739
But I am so glad
I got a chance to meet you.

1413
01:40:46,807 --> 01:40:50,004
You take care of yourself now.
Bye-bye.

1414
01:41:59,980 --> 01:42:02,278
Oh, Evelyn, hey!

1415
01:42:02,349 --> 01:42:04,817
Hey.

1416
01:42:04,885 --> 01:42:07,251
Do you like
my roses?

1417
01:42:07,321 --> 01:42:10,654
Since I can't get home
to look at my own roses...

1418
01:42:10,724 --> 01:42:13,090
I made myself
a paper garden.

1419
01:42:13,160 --> 01:42:16,652
<i>Got everything but the
bugs. They're lovely.</i>

1420
01:42:16,730 --> 01:42:19,995
You been here long?
Happy birthday!

1421
01:42:20,067 --> 01:42:22,558
Oh! I shouldn't have woken you up.

1422
01:42:22,636 --> 01:42:26,902
'Course you should've. Don't you never let
me sleep through a visitor's day, honey.

1423
01:42:26,974 --> 01:42:31,707
I look forward to them all
week. So do I, Mrs. Threadgoode.

1424
01:42:31,778 --> 01:42:35,111
[Gasp] Oh! I can't
believe you remembered.

1425
01:42:35,182 --> 01:42:39,380
You made me
fried green tomatoes!

1426
01:42:41,822 --> 01:42:43,847
Mmm!
They're delicious.

1427
01:42:43,924 --> 01:42:47,257
It's your recipe. Are they
cold? No. They're just the way...

1428
01:42:47,327 --> 01:42:51,593
we used to have 'em at
the Whistle Stop Cafe. Mmm!

1429
01:42:51,665 --> 01:42:55,601
You couldn't be sweeter to me
if you was my own daughter.

1430
01:42:55,669 --> 01:42:57,830
Here's your napkin.

1431
01:42:57,905 --> 01:42:59,930
And wait-wait-wait.

1432
01:43:00,007 --> 01:43:02,567
Queen, queen.

1433
01:43:05,746 --> 01:43:09,876
You know,
I don't feel 83.

1434
01:43:09,950 --> 01:43:14,080
It sorta slipped up on me.
[Whistle]

1435
01:43:16,190 --> 01:43:19,626
I never expected
to live this long.

1436
01:43:19,693 --> 01:43:25,290
'Course, the Lord takes us home
when he wants us.

1437
01:43:34,308 --> 01:43:37,937
Are you all right?

1438
01:43:38,011 --> 01:43:40,343
I was thinking
about Ruth.

1439
01:43:40,414 --> 01:43:43,212
After the trial
was over,

1440
01:43:43,283 --> 01:43:45,478
everything went back
to normal...

1441
01:43:45,552 --> 01:43:49,318
<i>till that fall
when Ruth lost her appetite.</i>

1442
01:43:49,389 --> 01:43:51,949
<i>By the time Doc Hadley
looked at her,</i>

1443
01:43:52,025 --> 01:43:56,223
<i>he said the cancer was so bad
she only had a couple of weeks.</i>

1444
01:43:56,296 --> 01:43:59,026
<i>Well, we moved her
to the Threadgoode house...</i>

1445
01:43:59,099 --> 01:44:03,934
<i>and put her downstairs
so she'd be more comfortable.</i>

1446
01:44:04,004 --> 01:44:08,498
<i>Sipsey moved in with her
and never left her side.</i>

1447
01:44:08,575 --> 01:44:10,702
<i>[Sipsey] Hold on, baby. I'm right here.</i>

1448
01:44:10,777 --> 01:44:15,441
<i>[Ninny] Idgie just prayed for a miracle.</i>

1449
01:44:34,735 --> 01:44:38,193
Now, listen to me.

1450
01:44:38,272 --> 01:44:40,797
Make sure he graduates.

1451
01:44:40,874 --> 01:44:45,072
And don't... let him
come to the funeral.

1452
01:44:45,145 --> 01:44:47,807
I don't want him going
through that mess.

1453
01:44:47,881 --> 01:44:51,180
Would you quit talkin'
like that?

1454
01:44:51,251 --> 01:44:53,742
What funeral?

1455
01:44:53,820 --> 01:44:56,186
You're gonna be back on
your feet feelin' just fine...

1456
01:44:56,256 --> 01:44:58,918
<i>in just a few days.</i>

1457
01:44:58,992 --> 01:45:01,893
<i>Just you wait.</i>

1458
01:45:01,962 --> 01:45:05,090
Oh, what's the matter,
son?

1459
01:45:10,937 --> 01:45:14,600
Well,
let's go for a walk.

1460
01:45:15,309 --> 01:45:16,901
<i>[Idgie] Did you get into a fight?</i>

1461
01:45:16,977 --> 01:45:19,673
I got punched
in the nose.

1462
01:45:19,746 --> 01:45:23,238
I can't play
like everyone else.

1463
01:45:23,317 --> 01:45:26,844
Did I ever tell you the
story about... the oysters?

1464
01:45:26,920 --> 01:45:29,388
All the millions of'em
just lying around...

1465
01:45:29,456 --> 01:45:34,291
And God put sand in one of'em,
and it makes a pearl. Oh.

1466
01:45:36,063 --> 01:45:38,725
Did I ever tell you about
Eva's three-legged dog?

1467
01:45:38,799 --> 01:45:40,892
How it never felt sorry
for itself...

1468
01:45:40,967 --> 01:45:44,596
and how I ought to be smarter than a
dumb dog and not feel sorry for myself.

1469
01:45:46,406 --> 01:45:49,739
You listen to everything
I say, don't you?

1470
01:45:49,810 --> 01:45:52,779
You get real mad at me
when I don't.

1471
01:45:52,846 --> 01:45:54,541
Well,

1472
01:45:57,017 --> 01:46:00,009
you know about
your mama.

1473
01:46:00,087 --> 01:46:02,578
She's sick.

1474
01:46:02,656 --> 01:46:04,681
Mm-hmm.

1475
01:46:06,226 --> 01:46:09,662
See, now is the time
for courage.

1476
01:46:09,730 --> 01:46:13,427
<i>I guess you already know
that there are...</i>

1477
01:46:13,500 --> 01:46:16,492
angels masqueradin' as people
walkin' around this planet,

1478
01:46:16,570 --> 01:46:19,733
and your mom's
the bravest one of those.

1479
01:46:24,010 --> 01:46:26,103
Come here.

1480
01:46:27,681 --> 01:46:29,740
<i>[Thunder]</i>

1481
01:46:33,820 --> 01:46:36,220
Mama, I can hit!
You should see me.

1482
01:46:36,289 --> 01:46:39,087
Idgie, she hit me in
the back with a curveball.

1483
01:46:39,159 --> 01:46:41,320
I didn't duck,
and I hardly cried.

1484
01:46:41,395 --> 01:46:44,853
She hit you?

1485
01:46:44,931 --> 01:46:48,924
Well, she did that
to me once too,

1486
01:46:49,002 --> 01:46:51,766
but I think
I did cry.

1487
01:46:53,673 --> 01:46:57,632
<i>Mama, I'm sorry
if you're sad.</i>

1488
01:46:57,711 --> 01:47:00,009
Well,

1489
01:47:00,080 --> 01:47:03,174
give me a big kiss then,
and I'll never be sad again.

1490
01:47:10,724 --> 01:47:13,625
And you best not be sad
neither.

1491
01:47:13,693 --> 01:47:16,924
You understand?

1492
01:47:16,997 --> 01:47:18,931
You promise?

1493
01:47:18,999 --> 01:47:21,024
Promise.

1494
01:47:21,101 --> 01:47:25,037
Attaboy.
You go and wash up.

1495
01:47:29,042 --> 01:47:32,307
<i>[Gasping, Wheezing]</i>

1496
01:47:48,862 --> 01:47:50,887
Sweet baby.

1497
01:47:54,868 --> 01:47:58,133
You two
be alone now.

1498
01:47:58,839 --> 01:48:02,502
Hey, girl.

1499
01:48:05,011 --> 01:48:07,070
No.

1500
01:48:09,015 --> 01:48:12,075
That's nice.

1501
01:48:13,086 --> 01:48:16,783
Will you do one thing
for me?

1502
01:48:16,857 --> 01:48:20,452
Yeah, anything.
Be good to yourself.

1503
01:48:20,527 --> 01:48:23,462
Even...

1504
01:48:23,530 --> 01:48:26,055
settle down if
you can find someone...

1505
01:48:26,132 --> 01:48:28,862
who can beat you
in poker.

1506
01:48:36,576 --> 01:48:41,536
There's so many things
I want to say to you.

1507
01:48:41,615 --> 01:48:44,140
No.

1508
01:48:44,985 --> 01:48:47,647
I love your stories.

1509
01:48:47,721 --> 01:48:50,656
Tell me a story,
Idgie.

1510
01:48:53,527 --> 01:48:57,361
[Whispering]
Oh, God.

1511
01:48:57,430 --> 01:49:00,524
<i>Go on,
you old bee charmer.</i>

1512
01:49:00,600 --> 01:49:04,263
<i>Tell me
a good tall tale.</i>

1513
01:49:05,672 --> 01:49:09,369
Tell me the one
about the lake.

1514
01:49:10,677 --> 01:49:15,307
What lake? The one...
that used to be here.

1515
01:49:17,450 --> 01:49:19,384
Oh.

1516
01:49:21,454 --> 01:49:25,015
Well, that was
just a lie.

1517
01:49:25,091 --> 01:49:27,855
I know that, fool.

1518
01:49:27,928 --> 01:49:29,987
Tell me anyway.

1519
01:49:30,063 --> 01:49:33,464
Tell me the story.

1520
01:49:35,035 --> 01:49:38,471
Well...

1521
01:49:40,507 --> 01:49:42,975
one time...

1522
01:49:43,043 --> 01:49:45,841
there was this lake.

1523
01:49:50,283 --> 01:49:54,652
And, uh, it was
right outside of town.

1524
01:49:54,721 --> 01:50:00,159
We used to go fishin' and
swimmin' and canoein' in it.

1525
01:50:00,226 --> 01:50:03,457
And see,
one November...

1526
01:50:03,530 --> 01:50:05,828
this big flock
of ducks...

1527
01:50:05,899 --> 01:50:10,927
came in and landed
on that lake and, uh,

1528
01:50:11,004 --> 01:50:15,839
and then the temperature dropped so fast
that the lake just froze right there.

1529
01:50:15,909 --> 01:50:18,173
And the, uh,

1530
01:50:18,244 --> 01:50:22,010
the ducks, they...

1531
01:50:22,082 --> 01:50:26,246
flew off, you see,
and took that lake with 'em.

1532
01:50:26,319 --> 01:50:29,550
And, uh,

1533
01:50:29,623 --> 01:50:34,617
now they say that lake is
somewhere over in Georgia.

1534
01:50:34,694 --> 01:50:37,754
Can you imagine?

1535
01:51:35,455 --> 01:51:38,720
It's all right,
honey.

1536
01:51:38,792 --> 01:51:44,761
Let her go.

1537
01:51:44,831 --> 01:51:49,063
You know,
Miss Ruth was a lady.

1538
01:51:49,135 --> 01:51:52,400
And a lady
always knows...

1539
01:51:52,472 --> 01:51:55,464
when to leave.

1540
01:51:55,542 --> 01:51:59,205
[Sigh]

1541
01:52:00,980 --> 01:52:05,076
<i>[Rev. Scroggins] When I think on
our departed sister, Ruth Jamison,</i>

1542
01:52:05,151 --> 01:52:08,245
<i>I'm reminded of our
Lord's Sermon on the Mount...</i>

1543
01:52:08,321 --> 01:52:10,789
<i>and how his teachings...</i>

1544
01:52:10,857 --> 01:52:15,294
<i>[Ninny] It's funny how
strong Ruth affected everyone,</i>

1545
01:52:15,361 --> 01:52:18,762
<i>even Smokey Lonesome.</i>

1546
01:52:18,832 --> 01:52:21,494
<i>When he died
a few years back...</i>

1547
01:52:21,568 --> 01:52:24,264
<i>he had one possession
on him,</i>

1548
01:52:24,337 --> 01:52:26,931
<i>a picture of Ruth.</i>

1549
01:52:28,308 --> 01:52:32,404
<i>He was in love with her
from the first time he saw her.</i>

1550
01:52:32,479 --> 01:52:35,346
<i>We all were.</i>

1551
01:52:41,321 --> 01:52:43,789
I shouldn't
a-told you this.

1552
01:52:45,725 --> 01:52:49,684
I hate death.
It scares me so.

1553
01:52:49,763 --> 01:52:52,288
Death is nothin'
to be afraid of!

1554
01:52:52,365 --> 01:52:55,425
Look at me. I'm at
the jumpin'-off place,

1555
01:52:55,502 --> 01:52:58,733
<i>and I ain't afraid
one bit.</i>

1556
01:52:58,805 --> 01:53:02,502
Oh, Ninny,
you're so brave.

1557
01:53:04,077 --> 01:53:08,013
Ruth and Idgie were brave,
not me.

1558
01:53:08,081 --> 01:53:11,448
I wouldn't be afraid
of death if I was you.

1559
